    <div class="game-section">
      <h3>How Stableford works</h3>
      <p>Instead of counting total strokes, Stableford awards points on each hole based on your score relative to par. High scores barely hurt; birdies and eagles win the round. The player with the most points wins.</p>
      <p>Marker uses the Modified Stableford point table, which rewards aggressive play and penalizes blow-up holes:</p>

      <table class="scoring-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Score</th>
            <th>vs. Par</th>
            <th>Points</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Double Eagle (Albatross)</td><td>−3</td><td>8</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Eagle</td><td>−2</td><td>5</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Birdie</td><td>−1</td><td>2</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Par</td><td>E</td><td>0</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Bogey</td><td>+1</td><td>−1</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Double Bogey or worse</td><td>+2 or more</td><td>−3</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <p>Marker automatically applies handicap strokes before calculating points — so the points on your scorecard already reflect your net score vs. par.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="game-section">
      <h3>The Quota System</h3>
      <p>The quota system adds a target to beat. Each player's quota is calculated as <strong>36 minus their course handicap</strong>. A 10-handicapper has a quota of 26 points. Beating your quota means you played better than expected; falling short means the course got you.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Quota keeps all handicap levels competitive in the same round</li>
        <li>It's easy to explain: "beat your number to win"</li>
        <li>Marker displays your running total vs. your quota as you play</li>
        <li>Final result is shown as points over or under quota (e.g. +4 quota)</li>
      </ul>
      <p>You can run Stableford with or without the quota system — Marker supports both. Without quota, the player with the highest raw point total wins.</p>
    </div>

